", "prob": 0.9946615099906921, "span": {"begin": 1272, "end": 1276}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "B cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8083667755126953, "span": {"begin": 1288, "end": 1295}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:11326"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "immunoglobulin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9807202219963074, "span": {"begin": 1319, "end": 1333}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "plasma and memory cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8740334510803223, "span": {"begin": 1364, "end": 1387}}, {"id": ["mesh:D016559"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "FK506", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9980598092079163, "span": {"begin": 1505, "end": 1510}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6776"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "STAT5", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9925189018249512, "span": {"begin": 1544, "end": 1549}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5465"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "peroxisome proliferator activated receptor", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9969180226325989, "span": {"begin": 1569, "end": 1611}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5465"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "PPAR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9960623979568481, "span": {"begin": 1613, "end": 1617}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5465"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "PPAR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9569569230079651, "span": {"begin": 1678, "end": 1682}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6776"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "STAT5", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9914500117301941, "span": {"begin": 1695, "end": 1700}}, {"id": ["mesh:C023036"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "perfluorooctanoic acid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995532035827637, "span": {"begin": 1756, "end": 1778}}, {"id": ["mesh:C023036"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "PFOA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9977082014083862, "span": {"begin": 1780, "end": 1784}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5465"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "PPARs", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9806364178657532, "span": {"begin": 1794, "end": 1799}}, {"id": ["mesh:C023036"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "PFOA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9954246878623962, "span": {"begin": 1968, "end": 1972}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5465"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "PPAR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9788159132003784, "span": {"begin": 2056, "end": 2060}}, {"id": ["mesh:C023036"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "PFOA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9943032264709473, "span": {"begin": 2083, "end": 2087}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6776"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "STAT5", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9914514422416687, "span": {"begin": 2100, "end": 2105}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3565"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-4", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9729613661766052, "span": {"begin": 2154, "end": 2158}}, {"id": ["mim:267430"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "TDAR", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9747820496559143, "span": {"begin": 2173, "end": 2177}}], "text": "The production of antibodies to T cell-dependent antigens is a coordinated process involving B cells, antigen-presenting cells, and T cell derived cytokines. The B cells are stimulated to proliferate and differentiate. The TDAR might be altered if any of these cell populations are affected.  IL-2 and IL-4 are produced and secreted by helper T cells. Both are important in the development of TDAR. IL-4 affects maturation and class switching of B cells as well as proliferation. Both events induce and enhance TDAR. IL-2 promotes differentiation of B cells, which stimulates differentiation of activated T cells to Th2 cells. The suppressed production of IL-2 and IL-4 impairs TDAR (Justiz Vaillant and Qurie 2020).  A mutant form of human IL-4, in which the tyrosine residue at position 124 is replaced by aspartic acid (hIL-4Y124D), was reported to specifically block IL-4 and IL-13-induced proliferation of B cells. In addition, hIL-4Y124D also strongly inhibited both IL-4- or IL-13-induced IgG4 and IgE synthesis in cultures of PBMCs, or highly purified sIgD+ B cells cultured in the presence of anti-CD40 monoclonal antibodies. IL-4 may be necessary to produce antibodies and to proliferate in B cells. The mutation of IL-4 may impair TDAR (Aversa, et al. 1993).   IL-4 stimulates B cells to proliferate, switch immunoglobulin classes, and differentiate to plasma and memory cells. Suppressing the production of these B cell related cytokines appears to impair TDAR, as evident from the results of FK506 treatment (Heidt, et al. 2010).  STAT5 is able to inhibit peroxisome proliferator activated receptor (PPAR)-regulated gene transcription. Conversely, ligand-activated PPAR can inhibit STAT5-regulated transcription. As a peroxisome proliferator, perfluorooctanoic acid (PFOA) induces PPARs. The suppression of TDAR has been observed with a no observable effect level (NOEL) of 1.88 mg/kg/d and lowest observed adverse effect level (LOEL) of 3.75 mg/kg/d for PFOA administered in drinking water over 15 days (Dewitt, et al. 2008). The increase in PPAR expression induced by PFOA may inhibit STAT5-regulated transcription, which is important for IL-4 production in TDAR.", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:22:44 +0000 2026"}